<header class="header">
  <h1>Plan Your Garden by Date, Not Guesswork</h1>

  <p class="lede">
    Most garden plans break down in short or unpredictable seasons because they rely on calendars.
    We use two climate constraints — frost timing and heat accumulation — to turn “maybe” into clear planting windows with margin.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    We build our tools around a simple idea: <strong>frost sets the boundaries</strong>, and <strong>heat accumulation determines what can mature</strong>.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card" aria-label="The 3-step climate planning system">
  <div class="cardHead">
    <h2>Our Climate Planning System</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Each step answers a different planning question. Together they form a complete timing system for short-season gardeners.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="tool" id="step-1">
    <h3>Step 1 — Find Your Frost Boundaries</h3>
    <p>
      Frost dates are your season edges: the typical last spring frost and first fall frost at 32°F / 0°C.
      These aren’t predictions — they’re stable planning anchors that help you build a schedule you can adjust in real weather.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button primary" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Use the Frost Date Finder</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="tool" id="step-2">
    <h3>Step 2 — Estimate Your Seasonal Heat (GDD)</h3>
    <p>
      Growing degree days (GDD) measure heat accumulation — the missing variable that explains why the same variety succeeds in one climate and fails in another.
      Days-to-maturity alone doesn’t tell you whether a crop can finish.
    </p>
    <p>
      Once you know your seasonal GDD, you can test whether specific crops have enough accumulated heat to mature before frost returns.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button primary" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="tool" id="step-3">
    <h3>Step 3 — Turn Your Season Into Dates</h3>
    <p>
      After defining your frost boundaries and confirming heat feasibility, convert those constraints into action:
      seed-start timing in spring, and “latest safe planting dates” in fall.
    </p>
    <p>
      These planners help you work forward from your last frost and backward from your first frost — with buffers that reflect real short-season conditions.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button" href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Spring Seed Starting Planner</a>
      <a class="button" href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">Fall Planting Planner</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card" aria-label="How climate-based garden planning works">
  <div class="cardHead">
    <h2>Plan Your Garden Around Your Real Season</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Most gardening advice assumes a long, forgiving growing season. If you garden in a cold or short-season climate, that assumption doesn’t hold up.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Traditional planting calendars give general date ranges, but they can’t account for how your specific location behaves. 
    In short seasons, success usually comes down to two measurable realities:
    <strong>when frost typically ends in spring and returns in fall</strong> — and 
    <strong>how much heat your area accumulates in between.</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    That’s why frost dates and growing degree days (GDD) need to be considered together. 
    Frost defines the edges of your season. GDD determines whether a crop can actually mature inside those edges.
    If you're new to this concept, start with
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">
      How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together
    </a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Seed packets list “days to maturity,” but that number assumes enough heat to reach maturity. 
    In cooler climates, that assumption can fail — even if you plant on time.
    We break down why in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">
      Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates
    </a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, it’s not just about planting early — it’s about building margin.
    A solid plan should work in a typical year, not just a warm one.
    For a step-by-step framework, see
    <a href="/guides/how-to-plan-a-garden-in-a-short-growing-season/">
      How to Plan a Garden in a Short Growing Season
    </a>.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The goal isn’t perfect prediction. It’s making confident decisions based on your actual climate.
  </p>
</section>